    <div class="post" id="post-8638">
      <div class="title">
     <h2><a href="http://greshams-law.com/2012/12/03/the-evolution-of-central-banking-in-england-america-1640-2012/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to The Evolution of Central Banking in England &amp; America: 1640 &#8211; 2012">The Evolution of Central Banking in England &#038; America: 1640 &#8211; 2012</a></h2>
     <div class="date">Dec 3, 2012</div>
      </div>
    <div class="clearer"></div>
    <div class="sticky_post"><p><a href="http://www.addogram.com/">Addogram.com</a> have come up with a large graphic (an &#8220;addogram&#8221;) about <a href="http://www.addogram.com/project/the-evolution-of-central-banks/">the evolution of central banking in England and America going as far back as 1640</a>. If you take a look at the zoomable image (click &#8220;Explore this addogram in high-resolution&#8221; once at the link above) you can see how UK &amp; US central banks affected (and were affected by) equity, bond and gold prices since 1840. Present dynamics in central bank balance sheets and long &amp; short-term yields looks eerily similar to 1930-1950. Interesting stuff.</p>
<p> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://greshams-law.com/2012/12/03/the-evolution-of-central-banking-in-england-america-1640-2012/#more-8638" class="more-link">continue reading &raquo;</a></p>
</div>
